First, we recognize that this problem can be approached using Möbius inversion. The given condition implies a Dirichlet convolution relationship. By substituting \( k = \frac{n}{d} \), we transform the sum into \(\sum_{k \mid n} \frac{n}{k} \cdot f(k) = 1\). This simplifies to \(\sum_{k \mid n} \frac{n}{k} \cdot f(k) = 1\). To solve for \( f(n) \), we use Möbius inversion. We define \( f'(k) = k \cdot f(k) \), leading to the equation \(\sum_{k \mid n} f'(k) = \frac{1}{n}\). Applying Möbius inversion, we find \( f'(n) = \sum_{d \mid n} \mu(d) \cdot \frac{n}{d} \). Converting back to \( f(n) \), we get \( f(n) = \sum_{d \mid n} \mu(d) \cdot d \). Next, we factorize 2023 as \( 2023 = 7 \times 17^2 \). The divisors of 2023 are 1, 7, 17, 119, 289, and 2023. We compute the Möbius function values for each divisor: - \(\mu(1) = 1\) - \(\mu(7) = -1\) - \(\mu(17) = -1\) - \(\mu(119) = \mu(7 \times 17) = 1\) - \(\mu(289) = \mu(17^2) = 0\) - \(\mu(2023) = \mu(7 \times 17^2) = 0\) Calculating the sum \(\sum_{d \mid 2023} \mu(d) \cdot d\): \[ 1 \cdot 1 + 7 \cdot (-1) + 17 \cdot (-1) + 119 \cdot 1 + 289 \cdot 0 + 2023 \cdot 0 = 1 - 7 - 17 + 119 = 96 \] Thus, \( f(2023) = \frac{96}{2023^2} \). Calculating \( 2023^2 = 4092529 \), we get the final answer: \[ \boxed{\dfrac{96}{4092529}} \]
